>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Flambert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English, French:  see  Flambard  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Flambard","meanings":["1  Norman, English: nickname from Old French  <i>flambard</i> ‘flaming torch’. There is no evidence to support an origin in a Continental Germanic personal name.","2  French: nickname from the same origin as (1)."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":19,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":50,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When James de Flambert I was born in 1240, in Ingrave, Essex, England, his father, Flambert, was 20 and his mother, Flambert, was 20. He married Catherine de Bernard in 1260, in Ingrave, Brentwood, Essex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1290, in Auriol, Alpes-de-Haute-Provence, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, France, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1240–1290":"1240–1290","1240–1270":"1240–1270","1266–1330":"1266–1330","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1259":"1259","1266":"1266","1220":"1220","1330":"1330","1240":"1240","about 1266":"umbes 1266","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Auriol, Alpes-de-Haute-Provence, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, France":"Auriol, Alpes-de-Haute-Provence, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, Prantsusmaa","Ingrave, Essex, England":"Ingrave, Brentwood, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Auriol, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, France":"Auriol, Alpes-de-Haute-Provence, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1240–1290":"1240–1290","1240–1270":"1240–1270","1266–1330":"1266–1330","1220–Male":"1220–Kuollut","1220–Female":"1220–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1266":"1266","1220":"1220",